ADR-005: Target Devices 

Status 
Approved 

 

Context 

Pocket Playground is a hub-based mobile application designed to host multiple mini-games and interactive tools that rely on device hardware (e.g., accelerometer, gyroscope, vibration, and audio output). 

The course requirements specify support for both Android and iOS platforms. The team must choose an approach that ensures cross-platform compatibility while maintaining consistent performance, UI behavior, and access to hardware APIs. 

Key considerations include: 

Differences in hardware capabilities across devices 

Variations in OS behavior and permissions handling 

UI consistency across platforms 

Development time constraints within the course timeline 

The team’s prior experience with JavaScript and React 

The architecture must support scalable growth of mini-games while minimizing platform-specific rework. 

 

Decision 

Pocket Playground will target both Android and iOS devices using a single shared codebase built with React Native. 

Platform-specific adjustments will only be implemented when necessary for hardware permissions, UI conventions, or device-level optimizations. 

 

Rationale 

React Native supports cross-platform development from a unified JavaScript codebase. 

Maintaining one shared architecture reduces development time and complexity. 

Supporting both Android and iOS increases usability and demonstrates broader mobile development competency. 

Cross-platform deployment aligns with industry best practices for scalable consumer apps. 

Limiting platform-specific customizations ensures the project remains within course scope and timeline. 

 

Consequences 

Positive: 

Broader accessibility across device ecosystems 

Reduced duplication of code 

Faster development compared to building two native apps 

Consistent user experience across platforms 

Demonstrates understanding of cross-platform architecture principles 

Negative: 

Potential platform-specific bugs requiring conditional logic 

Hardware sensor behavior may vary between Android and iOS devices 

UI elements may require minor adjustments to follow platform conventions 

Additional testing required to validate functionality on both platforms 
